ATTENTION ASD High School Students: Laptop Pick Up!

Laptop Pick-Up is Tuesday, August 25 from 8:00 am - 3:00 pm and Wednesday, August 26, from 10:00 am - 5:00 pm at the AHS Bus Loop (south side of AHS).

All Alamosa School District high school students will receive a district-issued laptop and may pick up their device at the AHS bus loop.

Students will need to bring an ID or have a parent/guardian with them who has an ID, and bring their parent-signed JS-E Student Technology Use Agreement form, or have a parent with them with to sign the form in order to pick up a device.

post_text:
ASD's Food Distribution Program will continue to operate August 24-September 11 during our three weeks of Hybrid Distance Learning using the summer food distribution routes.

Back to School Interviews will take place August 24-28, which are an opportunity to meet your child's teacher, discuss the supports your child needs, and receive the distance learning work for the week.

Distance learning starts the day after your Back to School Interview. Please make sure your child complete's the distance learning work provided by your child's teacher and returns it during their first in-person day.

Students will attend one day of in-person instruction each week during the weeks of August 31-September 4 and September 8-11.

Monday, August 31: Last Names A-F

Tuesday, September 1: Last Names G-L

Wednseday, September 2: Last Names M-Q

Thursday, September 3, Last Names R-Z

Full in-person instruction for all students, all grades begins September 14.

Thank you for all of your patience and support during this time!

#moosestrong

Superheros Wanted! Alamosa School District is looking for individuals who love children, are looking for a flexible schedule, and want to serve their community. ASD is looking for a diverse and reliable pool of substitutes that can support teachers when they require coverage. Apply for a substitute license through CDE and submit an application to substitute in Alamosa School District today!

A training for approved 2020-2021 ASD substitutes will take place on August 18, 2020.

‚Ä¢ $110 per day for PERA Teacher Retirees

‚Ä¢ $100 per day with a current Colorado Teacher License or a BA Degree and a Colorado Substitute Authorization License

‚Ä¢ $90 per day with a high school diploma and a Colorado Substitute Authorization License

Substitute applications are available online at
https://tinyurl.com/applyASD

CDE Substitute License applications are available at:
https://www.cde.state.co.us/cdeprof/licensure_subapp

Job Opening: High School Science Teacher

From one of our amazing AHS Science Teachers:

Hello,

I am asking for your help in advertising a position that we have open at Alamosa High School. We are looking for a science teacher that would be teaching physical and/or earth science.

We are located in the San Luis Valley right next to The Great Sand Dunes National Park, with many recreational trails, and a strong outdoor atmosphere. As well as a deep history of Colorado and New Mexico culture.

Alamosa High School has a approximately 600 students 9-12 grade, and a strong supportive 4 person science department. As well as opportunities to get involved via clubs, class sponsorships, and coaching.

Please have the applicant apply via our website or the link below.

Thank you for your help!

post_text:
Have you thought about a career in Family Child Care?
It provides an opportunity to be home with your own children while providing care for the children in our community.

Steps to Becoming a Family Child Care Provider:

1. Contact SLV Early Childhood Council at www.eccslv.org or 719-937-4010

2. Complete and sign the licensing application and get fingerprinted.

3. Confirm compliance with any zoning or building ordinances.

4. Consult with a SLV Licensing Specialist (Armando Avila 719-347-7378 or armando.avila@state.co.us)

5. Complete Training Requirements

6. Mail Application

7. Contact the Department of Human Services (Alamosa 719-589-2581) to let them know you are available to provide services for the Child Care Assistance Program (CCAP)

Early Childhood Council SLV

In addition to our food distribution program, all Alamosa School District families are eligible to sign up for the Meals-to-You Program - thanks to a partnership with Baylor University and the USDA.

Every two weeks, 10 breakfasts and 10 lunches are SHIPPED to homes for each child in the home that is 1-18 years old, and it is completely FREE.

This is a great option for those families who cannot get to a food distribution site.

Register today at: https://mealstoyou.org/emergency-meals-to-you-application/

You must sign up by May 28! Boxes will be provided on a first come, first served basis, so sign up online today!

post_text: To the AHS Class of 2020 - The faculty and staff of Alamosa High School want you to know that we are working behind the scenes to prepare for a graduation event that is as special as each member of your class! Graduation will be on May 16th and details have been mailed out. Every option available is being taken to create the most memorable experience possible under the current restrictions from local, state, and federal officials. The event will be filmed, photographed, recorded, and streamed for the community and shared with you and your families for free. If local and state officials ease restrictions during the summer to allow for large gatherings - AHS will plan a BBQ Bash for the Class of 2020. We are in this together!

Attention Alamosa Community:
THANK YOU for making sure your child stays at home and does not connect in person with their friends.

In person contact can be very dangerous for families. Although children make look healthy it is so important that they continue to shelter in place. Some children can be asymptomatic with the cornoavirus and quickly give it to their friends who take it back to their family members.

During this time, please encourage your child to connect virtually in healthy ways.

THANK YOU for your diligent work keeping our community safe by keeping children at home!

It is very important to ASD that our students are safe! Zoom enabled safety features over the weekend on ASD Zoom Rooms.
Your child may experience a delay when attempting to get into a Zoom Room since all participants are now required to go to a waiting room before being granted access by the host (teacher). In addition, Zoom Rooms can be password protected and locked once participants are allowed in.
Other safety features include participants muted upon entry and not allowed to share their screen unless the host (teacher) grants permission.
Although the safety features may take a bit of time for everyone to get used to, it is critical that we keep Zoom Rooms secure.

post_text:
As of Monday, March 16, 2020, Alamosa School District has not canceled any post-Spring Break school days. Based on the number of National, State and County mandates, safeguards, and protocols being issued, it appears rather inevitable our district will be affected, whether it be abbreviated or canceled scheduling.

Our District and SLV leaders are continuing to stay in communication to determine the best plan for Alamosa School District.

It is our desire to keep students and staff safe while maintaining delivery of educational services including nutrition for our students.

Please anticipate further communication this Wednesday afternoon.

post_text:
The Alamosa School District would like to inform parents and students that we are taking extra precautions to keep students and staff safe and healthy during this time of COVID-19. The district is providing additional cleaning and disinfecting of classrooms, buildings and buses. You can take these steps to help keep your family safe. Wash your hands frequently and for at least 20 seconds with soap and water, especially after you cough or sneeze. Hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol can be used if soap and water are not nearby. Avoid touching your face. Avoid sharing food or drinks.

If your child has a fever above 100.4 or has other respiratory symptoms (cough or shortness of breath) please keep them home from school until they have not had a fever for 24 hours (without the use of fever reducing medications).

The state of Colorado has set up a hotline to obtain the most up to date information on COVID-19. The number is 1-877-462-2911. Governor Polis has created a guidance for school closures.

shared_text:
Alamosa Elementary School
February 25 at 5:46 PM ¬∑

Percussionist, composer, and storyteller Cory Hills thrives on breaking down musical barriers through creative, interdisciplinary projects. These last two weeks, he has been meeting Alamosa Elementary School students and running percussive storytelling workshops! Percussive Storytelling is a program that brings classical music and storytelling to kids in fun and accessible ways. He hails from Los Angeles, California where he is an active performer, composer, and recording artist, as well as a member of the Grammy-nominated Los Angeles Percussion Quartet.

He was brought to Alamosa through the Artist in Residency Program in Adams State Music and Art department and the Nation Endowment for the Arts grant. For a whole month, he is working with students of all ages around our beautiful valley.

Our students have been writing stories and setting them to music to perform at this weeks assembly that Cory Hills is hosting here at AES 3-5!

post_text:
Making history again, our girls MS XC team are back to back state champions. The girls race was very exciting. Elizabeth was in 3rd place with 25m to go. She passed up last year's winner and tied exactly down to the tenth of a second with our very own Araceli Molina. The officials looked at the photos to decide who the champion was.
Our team score was 35 points, the lowest in our history. And.... if we had run in the other division against the 4a and 5am schools, we would have tied 1st place.

What an incredible day for our ladies.
1st- Elizabeth McQuitty-14:01.9
2nd- Araceli Molina-14:01.9
7th- Sarah De La Cerda
18th- Vanessa Villalva
22nd- Victoria Gifford
24th- Ema Bradley
33rd- Jayden Wubben

They were incredibly close for a race with 251 runners in it.

The boys placed 16th overall. They struggled a bit on Saturday, but we still had some personal records.
Mario Villalba-19th
Jeremiah De LaCerda-80th
Dylan Crowder-97th
Mason Gonzales-111th
Johnathan Ramirez-146th
Tyler Dokson-189th
Carsten Kirkland-210th

Out of 249 runners.

post_text:
National School Bus Safety Week, October 21-25, 2019

National School Bus Safety Week in October is the ideal time to reinforce bus safety rules among students and express gratitude to your bus drivers and staff for their hard work and professionalism. National School Bus Safety Week is an active and evolving public education program and an excellent way for parents, students, teachers, motorists, school bus operators, school administrators, and other interested parties - to join forces and address the importance of school bus safety. Please join us in recognizing the hard work of our bus drivers and the importance of bus safety!
